President-elect Trump‚Äôs refusal to release his tax returns makes it clear he has something to hide from the American people.  Either President-elect Trump releases his tax returns or he explains to the people he works for why he believes he is entitled to keep secrets.

The opioid epidemic is not a partisan issue, and a strong partnership between the federal government and our state is essential to an effective response. I led the effort in the Senate calling on bipartisan leaders in Congress to include $1 billion in additional investments to address opioid abuse. Last month I urged Governor Scott Walker to apply for the new state grant funding.   Today, I am pleased to hear that Governor Walker has directed the Wisconsin Department of Health Services to apply for this federal funding that will help advance local prevention, treatment and recovery efforts. This is a significant step forward for communities fighting the opioid epidemic across Wisconsin.

We have a broken system in Washington that prohibits the federal government from negotiating lower prescription drug prices for our senior citizens. We need to change that so we can help lower out-of-pocket costs for seniors.  I have long championed efforts to allow the government to negotiate directly with pharmaceutical companies to get better prices on lifesaving medicines instead of increasing drug company profits. The Medicare Prescription Drug Price Negotiation Act is a critical proposal that would help safeguard the Medicare program and keep our promises to seniors and taxpayers.

"Sen. Tammy Baldwin is again asking the federal Department of Veterans Affairs to investigate the Wisconsin Veterans Home at King following a hazardous liquid oxygen incident there and additional federal health violations.   "Accounts of neglect, staffing shortages and crumbling facilities is alarming, and recent reports of systematic attempts to cover-up and obscure incidents of concern from state and federal oversight demands action," Baldwin wrote in a letter sent Wednesday to Veterans Affairs Secretary Robert McDonald."

The public deserves to know if their President has taken advantage of tax loopholes or put his income or profits in off shore accounts in order to pay a lower tax rate than Wisconsin middle class families. People also deserve to know how President-elect Trump will personally benefit from foreign deals or his own tax cut proposals.   Either President-elect Trump releases his tax returns or he explains to the people he works for why he believes he is entitled to keep secrets. WAOW Newsline 9

President-elect Trump is a walking, talking, tweeting conflict of interest who seems intent on rewriting the rules to make them work for himself. The American people need to be able to trust that the President of the United States is putting the interests of the people first, not his own. In order for President-elect Trump to earn this trust, he must fully divest his financial interests and put them away in a truly blind trust.  Today, I joined U.S. Senator Elizabeth Warren and Democratic members of Congress in introducing the Presidential Conflicts of Interest Act of 2017 in the United States Senate and House that would require the President and Vice President to disclose and divest any potential financial conflicts of interest. It also would require presidential appointees to recuse themselves from any specific matters involving the President's financial conflicts of interest that come before their agencies.

I expect Senator Jeff Sessions to use his confirmation hearing this week to leave no doubt that he is fully dedicated to the idea that all Americans deserve the freedom and opportunity to pursue their hopes and dreams. That is the promise of America and everyone needs to trust that he will faithfully make sure we keep it. If Senator Sessions cannot or will not make a full commitment to act on violence borne out of hatred based on race, religion, disability, sexual orientation, gender identity or any other characteristic, then he has no place serving as America‚Äôs top law enforcement official.

As Senator Jeff Sessions' nomination hearing begins, I am calling on him to make a full commitment to combat hate crimes.   All Americans deserve an Attorney General that is committed to an America that stands united in embracing the diversity of its people.

In 2012, I was elected to the U.S. Senate and the people of Wisconsin did not send me here to take their health care away.  I took to the Senate Floor to demand that my Republican colleagues listen -- not to me -- but to the calls from people that we are here to represent and fight for.

President-elect Trump was a walking, talking, tweeting conflict of interest yesterday and he remains one today.   The fact that the President-elect refuses to release his tax returns proves that he thinks he is entitled to keep secrets, and his refusal to fully divest his financial interests and put them away in a fully blind trust shows he is more interested in doing what is best for himself‚Äînot the American people.

Given that Transportation Secretary nominee Elaine Chao has previously opposed #BuyAmerica requirements, I have had serious concerns about her commitment to a top priority of mine.   But, I‚Äôm pleased that she made a commitment today to support Buy America reforms and will work to keep President-elect Trump's promise to "buy American and hire American."

As someone who didn‚Äôt have access to quality health insurance until my twenties, I was proud to champion a reform that allows young people to stay on their parents‚Äô insurance until age 26.   Last night, I introduced an amendment that would protect this popular reform.   Young adults are our next generation of leaders, so I will continue to fight against Congressional Republican efforts to rob them of affordable health care.

America has made great progress over the last eight years with an Administration that has taken seriously a shared responsibility to pass on to the next generation a country that is more equal, not less equal.   Every American citizen deserves a government that is as good as they are and they are right to demand that our Attorney General, and our Department of Justice, are committed to the principle that racism, discrimination, and hate-based crimes will not be tolerated in America. All Americans also deserve a strong commitment from our Attorney General, America‚Äôs top law enforcement official, to act on violence borne out of hatred based on race, religion, disability, sexual orientation, gender identity or any other characteristic. It‚Äôs also very important to me that we have an Attorney General who will be a strong supporter of constitutional rights. At a time when voting rights and the constitutional right of women to make their own, personal reproductive health care decisions are under attack across our country, we need an Attorney General who will stay true to these constitutional freedoms and not be driven by politics.   For me, the vote on Senator Jeff Sessions‚Äô confirmation to be our next United States Attorney General is a moral choice guided by my strong belief that all Americans deserve equal opportunity and the freedom to pursue their hopes and dreams. That is the promise of America and I have committed myself and my life‚Äôs work to make sure we keep it. After meeting with Senator Sessions, I cannot support his confirmation to be our next Attorney General because I don‚Äôt have faith that he shares these beliefs and that he will embrace these commitments, and our shared responsibility to move our nation forward for all Americans.

It is my privilege to represent the many dedicated Wisconsinites serving in America‚Äôs all-volunteer Army, whether part of the National Guard, Reserves, or Active Component, as well as their families.  I‚Äôve also been proud to advocate for the hardworking men and women in our state‚Äôs defense industry who support our country‚Äôs soldiers, building the platforms and equipment that ensure our servicemembers complete their missions successfully and safely.  I would like to thank Secretary of the Army Eric Fanning for selecting me for the Army's Decoration for Distinguished Civilian Service Award‚Äì it‚Äôs truly an honor.

I'm calling on all of President-elect Trump's nominees to disclose any pay out deals and golden parachutes they will receive as they enter public service. The Trump nominees also need to explicitly detail how they will recuse themselves from matters relating to their former employers or industries. Today, we honor and remember the legacy of Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.  Through his life‚Äôs work, Dr. King taught us the power of working towards something bigger than ourselves. He taught us the power and strength we gain as a community when we commit ourselves to the idea that we are all in it together.

President-elect Trump repeatedly promised to withdraw from TPP, in fact he made a pledge to do it on Friday. He must be held accountable to this pledge and he needs to keep his word to American workers. I have introduced legislation to help him keep this promise if he is serious about making Washington work for Wisconsin's working class.   TPP is a bad deal for American workers. Instead of creating an even playing field, this deal increases the global race to the bottom in worker pay. American manufacturing jobs will continue to go abroad as Buy America rules are further eroded. The agreement gives foreign companies the ability to challenge American laws in secret international courts. Negotiated behind closed doors, TPP reflects the desires of multinational corporations, not the Wisconsin workers who will have to live with its consequences.

Wisconsinites sent me to Washington to stand up to powerful interests and fight for Wisconsin's working class. I will hold President Trump accountable.  Watch my conversation with Chris Hayes and Senator Chris Murphy on All In with Chris Hayes.

Wisconsin has a long and proud tradition of supporting quality public education for every student. In fact, from our beginning in 1848, the state constitution provided for a free education for all children in the state. This is a tradition I have a deep respect for and have worked to move forward. It is very important to me that our next Secretary of Education respects this tradition and is committed to it, but after meeting with Betsy DeVos, and participating in the hearing as a member of the Senate Health, Education, Labor, and Pensions Committee, I don‚Äôt believe she does.    Nor do I believe she is qualified to lead America‚Äôs efforts to give more students access to a higher education. We have a student loan debt crisis in our country and this nominee did not earn my trust that she is prepared to act and make higher education more affordable for students and families.  Betsy DeVos lacks the public education experience and qualifications for this job and she would not rule out defunding public schools. For all these reasons and more, I will not support Betsy DeVos‚Äô confirmation to be our next Secretary of Education.‚Äù

I voted against the PATRIOT Act more than a decade ago because I believed it would open the door to government overreach. Since then, we have seen that secret, domestic surveillance programs have crossed the line and infringed on people‚Äôs privacy.   President Trump‚Äôs nomination of Congressman Mike Pompeo for CIA Director is deeply troubling given his record of supporting those programs as well as calling for far-reaching new surveillance activities that would threaten civil liberties guaranteed by our Constitution.   I believe we need to strengthen our counterterrorism efforts and protect the privacy and freedoms of law abiding Americans. We can and must do both. However, I don‚Äôt have confidence that Mike Pompeo shares this belief so that is why I did not support his confirmation.

Let there be no doubt, global climate change is real. It is a fact and no "alternative facts" can change it. The question is not whether climate change is occurring, but how our nation is going to take it on.  Taking action on climate change will ensure that we keep our promise to future generations to confront today‚Äôs challenges and pass on a world better than we found it. These irresponsible and shameful actions run counter to our American values, the Constitution, our national security and economic interests. President Trump took an oath eleven days ago to preserve, protect and defend the Constitution of the United States, but since he was sworn into office he has pursued a go it alone approach of extremism. With this Supreme Court nomination, President Trump has made it clear he has no interest in being a President for all Americans and that he is intent on creating more division in our country. Instead of putting forward a mainstream nominee for the vacant Supreme Court seat, he has offered someone who will have a hard time earning bipartisan support.  The importance of the Supreme Court and the decisions they make have a profound effect on the daily lives of all Americans so I will do my job to fully review Judge Gorsuch‚Äôs record. I also look forward to meeting with him because I have a number of concerns and questions about his deeply troubling record, particularly his rulings against disabled students, against workers, and against women‚Äôs reproductive health care.  The American people deserve an independent Supreme Court Justice who will protect the constitutional rights and freedoms of all Americans, not someone who will put his own political preferences above the law and legislate President Trump‚Äôs far right agenda from the bench of our nation‚Äôs highest court. That is the test I will apply as I give fair consideration to this nomination.

The people of Wisconsin deserve a Treasury Secretary who will work to build an economy that works for everyone, not just those at the top.

I am very concerned that the SEC has enabled Wall Street‚Äôs aggressive pursuit of short-term profits at the expense of job creation and long-term growth.   In 1981, American corporations spent $3.6 billion on buybacks. In 1982, the SEC gave corporate executives the green light on buybacks, telling them they would not be charged with stock price manipulation if they bought back their shares on the open market. By 1984, that number exploded to $37 billion, an increase of over 900 percent. Today, the numbers are astronomical: over the last five years S&P 500 companies alone spent over $2.5 trillion buy back their own stock.   The SEC needs to tighten its rules governing buybacks.
